Queens Boulevard, west from Fifty-seventh Avenue, showing an area of Queens Boulevard prior to its widening. View No. 1 shows in the foreground No. 58 (old No.) Queens Boulevard at the S.W. corner of above Boulevard and Fifty-sixth Avenue. It was the property of one Arnoldi prior to 1873. Also seen in this view is the steeple of the new First Presbyterian Church of Newtown. Its steeple has since been removed. View No. 2 shows the north side of the Boulevard. The extension of Mrs. Raymond's house at the right foreground is west of Fifty-sixth Avenue. (Laconia Street also known as Horsebrook Road). View No. 3 shows the house alone prior to its removal. View No. 2 also shows the old First Presbyterian Church in the background. View No. 4 shows the house according to E.L. Armbruster to now, 1925, be on the north (west) side of Fifty-seventh Avenue (Caldwell Avenue) about 50 feet west (south) of Van Horn Street. However it does not appear in the 1929 Atlas of Queens County.

April 1923.
View 2: August 1924.
View 3: February 8, 1924.
View 4: July 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Queens Boulevard (tracks thereon) at and adjoining the S.W. corner of Fifty-seventh Avenue. Shown at the corner is the home of Samuel Reune in 1776 which was also known as the Bretoni ers' house. It was remodelled in 1865 by J. Van Riper, a builder. The hip roof was converted to that seen in the views. This builder also believes that the structure adjoining it was the first Baptist Church building of Newtown. The first mentioned house was still standing in November 1933.

1922
View 2: April 1923
View 3: February 1924
View 4: May 1926.

No. 63 belonged to Mrs. Bauch from 1873 to 1891 and No. 49 to Mrs. Raymond. View No. 2 of this set is similar, eliminating No. 85.

Queens Boulevard, at the S. W. corner of 57th Avenue, showing the Samuel Reime House, a pre-Revolutionary house. It was also known as the Arnold's House. One Bretonier was the owner in 1852. The house was altered in 1865. Eugene L. Armbruster is authority for the above data.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
